# Intent Data Activation: Turning Signals Into Actions That Generate Pipeline

This skill addresses the gap between buying intent data and using it.
Most B2B SaaS companies that purchase ZoomInfo Intent, Bombora Company
Surge, or G2 Buyer Intent do one of two things with it: they add a score
to a contact record in their CRM and hope the sales team notices, or
they build a dashboard that no one looks at after the first month. Neither
produces pipeline.

Intent data earns its cost when it changes what happens next for a
specific account. A signal without a workflow is just data. This skill
encodes the workflow design decisions that connect a signal to a response,
the threshold logic that determines which signals are worth acting on,
the routing decisions that determine whether a signal goes to a rep or a
campaign, and the measurement framework that tells you whether the
activation is working.

---

## HOW TO SET UP THIS SKILL

Provide:

- Which intent data provider or providers you have: ZoomInfo Intent,
  Bombora, G2 Buyer Intent, 6sense, Demandbase, or other
- Your CRM: HubSpot, Salesforce, or other
- How intent data currently flows into your CRM, if at all
- Whether you have an SDR or BDR team handling outbound
- Your current ICP: the firmographic and behavioral profile of your
  best-fit accounts
- What, if anything, you are currently doing with intent signals

---

## The Core Problem: Intent Data Without Activation Logic

Intent data vendors sell on the premise that knowing which accounts
are researching your category is enough to drive action. It is not.
The signal tells you that an account is interested. It does not tell
you how interested, whether they match your ICP, what they should
receive next, or who owns the response. Without that logic built into
your CRM or marketing automation platform, the signal expires unused.

Intent signals decay fast. A Bombora Company Surge score that spikes
on a Monday and is not acted on by Wednesday has already lost
significant value. Accounts in active research mode are evaluating
multiple vendors simultaneously. The team that responds first with
relevant messaging wins more conversations than the team with the
best product but the slowest activation.

---

## Step 1: Signal Triage Before Building Any Workflow

Before building activation workflows, determine which signals are
worth acting on. Not all intent signals represent real buying behavior.

**Signal quality by source type:**

First-party signals (your own website, your own HubSpot or Salesforce
data): Highest quality. An account visiting your pricing page three
times in a week is a more reliable signal than an account showing
Bombora surge on a topic adjacent to your category. First-party
signals should always take priority in your activation logic.

G2 Buyer Intent: High quality for software categories. An account
actively reviewing products in your category on G2 has demonstrated
vendor evaluation behavior. This is a reliable buying signal, not
just research behavior.

Bombora Company Surge: Medium quality. Surge above baseline on a
relevant topic indicates research activity, but topic selection
matters enormously. Broad topics produce noise. Narrow, category-
specific topics produce signal. Evaluate whether your topic selections
are tight enough to filter out accounts that are researching adjacent
problems rather than your specific solution.

ZoomInfo Intent: Variable quality depending on how topics are
configured and how the score is weighted. Treat it as a directional
indicator to be validated against ICP fit before routing to reps.

**The ICP filter must come before the intent filter:**

A high-intent signal from a company outside your ICP is not worth
acting on at the rep level. It may be worth a retargeting impression,
but it should not generate an SDR task. Build your ICP qualification
criteria into the workflow before the intent routing step. Sequence:
does the account fit ICP? Then: what is the intent signal strength?
Then: what happens next?

---

## Step 2: Threshold Design

Intent signals need thresholds to be actionable. A workflow that fires
on every intent signal generates noise and trains your reps to ignore
the alerts. A workflow with thresholds that are too high misses accounts
that are genuinely in-market.

**Threshold framework for a mid-market B2B SaaS company:**

Tier 1 (immediate rep response within 24 hours):
Account is in ICP. Account has no open opportunity in CRM. Intent
signal is first-party (pricing page visit, demo page visit, returning
visitor from known company domain) or G2 Buyer Intent active. Signal
has been active for three or more days rather than a single spike.

Tier 2 (campaign enrollment, SDR sequence within 48 hours):
Account is in ICP. No open opportunity. Bombora surge score above
your chosen threshold (typically 60 or above on a 100-point scale,
but calibrate to your category). Or ZoomInfo intent score elevated
on two or more relevant topics simultaneously.

Tier 3 (retargeting only, no direct outreach):
Account shows intent signal but does not fully match ICP. Or signal
is weak or single-topic. Enroll in LinkedIn retargeting or paid
display. Do not generate SDR task.

Existing customers and open opportunities: Flag for customer success
or the account executive who owns the relationship. Intent signals
from accounts already in pipeline or already a customer are expansion
signals, not new business signals. Route accordingly.

---

## Step 3: Workflow Architecture in HubSpot or Salesforce

The workflow must do five things: receive the signal, check ICP
fit, apply threshold logic, route to the right response, and log
the trigger for measurement.

**HubSpot workflow structure for intent activation:**

Enrollment trigger: Contact property or company property updated
by the intent data integration (ZoomInfo, Bombora, or G2 native
integration, or imported via CSV or Zapier if no native integration
exists).

Step 1: Check company properties against ICP criteria. Employee
count in range, industry match, revenue range if available. If
not ICP fit, enroll in Tier 3 retargeting list. Exit workflow.

Step 2: Check for existing open deal. If open deal exists, create
task for deal owner. Exit main workflow. If no open deal, proceed.

Step 3: Apply signal threshold logic. If Tier 1 criteria met,
create task for assigned SDR or BDR with high priority, due within
24 hours. Send internal Slack or email notification. Log intent
trigger in contact timeline. If Tier 2 criteria met, enroll in
outbound sequence (if SDR team exists) or in marketing nurture
sequence with intent-aware messaging. Log trigger. If Tier 3,
add to retargeting audience only.

Step 4: Set a re-enrollment window. If the account takes no action
and the signal persists for 14 days, re-evaluate. If signal drops,
remove from active queue. If account converts to opportunity, exit
intent workflows entirely.

**The logging step is not optional:**

Every time the workflow fires, log the intent trigger, the tier it
was routed to, and the date in the contact or company record. Without
this log you cannot measure activation effectiveness. You will not
know whether your Tier 1 accounts converted to opportunities at a
higher rate than Tier 2, and you will not be able to improve your
thresholds over time.

---

## Step 4: Messaging That Uses the Signal

An intent-triggered outreach that does not reference the signal
context wastes the information advantage the signal provides.
A generic SDR sequence sent to an intent-triggered account is only
marginally better than a cold sequence. The signal tells you something
about what the account is researching. The outreach should reflect that.

**What to reference without being creepy:**

Do not say: "I see you have been researching supply chain software."
Accounts find this unsettling and it signals surveillance, not
relevance.

Do say: "We work with a lot of supply chain teams who are evaluating
how to get better pipeline visibility right now. Most of them tell
us the biggest gap is X." This acknowledges the research context
without referencing the signal directly.

Intent signal types map to different message angles:

G2 Buyer Intent: The account is actively comparing vendors. Lead with
differentiation and proof. They are already sold on the category. The
question is why you versus the alternatives. "I noticed [company] is
evaluating options in this space. Here is what we typically hear from
teams who switched to us from [competitor]."

Bombora surge on a problem topic: The account is researching a
problem, not yet a solution. Lead with problem validation and
perspective. Not a product pitch. "Most teams we talk to in [industry]
are dealing with X right now. Here is how we have seen the best ones
approach it."

First-party high-intent (pricing page, demo page): The account
has expressed direct commercial interest. Make it easy to take the
next step. The message should be short, direct, and low friction.
"I saw [company] spent some time on our pricing page recently. Happy
to walk you through options based on your team size and use case."

---

## Step 5: Measuring Activation Effectiveness

Intent data activation has two measurement problems. First, you need
to know whether activated accounts convert to pipeline at a higher rate
than non-activated accounts of the same ICP profile. Second, you need
to know which signal types and thresholds are driving the most pipeline
so you can tune the workflows.

**The two reports that tell you if activation is working:**

Conversion rate by intent tier: Tier 1 accounts that received a
rep response within 24 hours versus Tier 2 accounts in sequence
versus Tier 3 in retargeting only. If Tier 1 is not converting to
opportunities at a meaningfully higher rate than Tier 2, your Tier 1
threshold is miscalibrated. Either you are routing too many accounts
to Tier 1 (diluting rep attention) or the signal quality is lower
than expected.

Signal-to-opportunity time: How many days between the first intent
signal and opportunity creation, on average. If this number is
improving, your activation speed is working. If it is stagnant,
the delay is in the rep response, the sequence, or the threshold
logic triggering too late in the research cycle.

Run both reports quarterly. Adjust thresholds based on what you see.
Intent data activation is not a set-it-and-forget configuration.
The signals your category produces shift as the market matures, as
new competitors enter, and as your ICP evolves.

---

## Common Activation Failures and How to Fix Them

**The rep ignores intent alerts:**
Cause: Too many alerts, low signal quality, or alerts arriving in
a channel reps do not monitor. Fix: Tighten Tier 1 threshold to
reduce volume. Move alerts to the channel reps already use (Slack,
CRM task, email). Add context to the alert so reps understand why
this account is flagged.

**The workflow fires but nothing converts:**
Cause: ICP filter is too loose, signal threshold is too low, or
messaging does not reflect the signal context. Fix: Audit the last
30 Tier 1 accounts. What percentage were genuinely ICP fit? What
was the SDR response time? What sequence were they enrolled in?
Find the break in the chain before adjusting thresholds.

**Intent data stops flowing into CRM:**
Cause: Native integrations break silently. CSV imports become
someone's weekly manual task that eventually stops happening. Fix:
Build a weekly check into your RevOps routine: verify that the
last intent data update in CRM occurred within the expected window.
Set a calendar reminder. Do not rely on the integration to alert
you when it breaks.

